<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bdd257c9369fb68e1d06923d10ff789e?s=50"></div><header><strong>Removal of dispatch_once() in Swift 3?</strong> from <string>Ben Rimmington</string> &lt;me at benrimmington.com&gt;<p>June 16, 2016 at 10:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>William Shipley wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; I may be missing something, but I don’t understand how to get the behavior<br>&gt; of dispatch_once() without a bunch more code in cases in which I was using<br>&gt; it to initialize “lazy-ish&quot; instance variables.<br></p><p>In Objective-C, the `dispatch_once_t` predicate *must* be a static or global<br>variable (which is automatically initialized to zero).<br></p><p>&lt;https://developer.apple.com/reference/dispatch/1447169-dispatch_once&gt;<br></p><p>In any case, `dispatch_once` and `pthread_once` are not available. See the<br>&quot;Interacting with C APIs&quot; chapter in the pre-release &quot;Using Swift with Cocoa<br>and Objective-C (Swift 3)&quot;.<br></p><p>&lt;https://developer.apple.com/swift/resources/&gt;<br></p><p>Note that &quot;lazy stored properties&quot; (i.e. `lazy var` instance variables)<br>are *not* safe to access by multiple threads simultaneously.<br></p><p>-- Ben<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
